            <z:AutomaticTag>
               <rdf:value>Layout guidelines</rdf:value>
            </z:AutomaticTag>
        </dc:subject>
        <dc:subject>
            <z:AutomaticTag>
               <rdf:value>Process model comprehension</rdf:value>
            </z:AutomaticTag>
        </dc:subject>
        <dc:title>Verifying the understandability of BPMN diagrams: a biometric study on the cognitive impact of layout guidelines</dc:title>
        <dcterms:abstract>The layout of Business Process Model and Notation (BPMN) diagrams plays a critical role in determining how effectively users interpret process information. However, empirical evidence regarding the cognitive impact of layout quality remains limited. This study investigates the influence of visual layout guidelines on the understandability of BPMN models using a multimodal biometric approach. We conducted a controlled experiment in which 37 participants interpreted two BPMN diagrams: one that adhered to layout best practices and another that deliberately violated them. During the task, their physiological responses were monitored via eye-tracking and EEG. Results indicate that models following layout guidelines significantly reduce cognitive load, improve attention distribution, and enhance task performance. Participants exposed to disorganized layouts showed increased EEG theta activity, more dispersed eye fixations, and lower accuracy rates. The study triangulates biometric data with subjective assessments to provide a comprehensive understanding of how layout structure affects comprehension. These findings reinforce the value of user-centered modeling practices and highlight the potential of biometric methods for evaluating the cognitive effectiveness of process representations.</dcterms:abstract>
        <dc:date>2026-01-01</dc:date>
        <z:shortTitle>Verifying the understandability of BPMN diagrams</z:shortTitle>
        <z:libraryCatalog>ScienceDirect</z:libraryCatalog>
